<br />
The 4-strength symbols tend to get screwed royally by the figure exchange tile. So I like to draw into those late as trump cards (or hopefully draw into them after everyone has played their figure exchange tiles). <br />
<br />
I tried a strategy playing with all the ships in my opening hand and that was a disaster. I played them all right away (to secure cities and double village harbours) but I found I really need a ship or two later on in the game. <br />
<br />
Finally I settled on using Samurai ONLY in my opening hand. This way, i&#39;m totally immune to Figure Exchange and can make a strong play for Edo. So I tried:<br />
<br />
3 Samurai<br />
2 Samurai<br />
2 Samurai<br />
1 Samurai<br />
1 Ronin<br />
<br />
I was debating on starting with the Ronin versus another 1 Samurai. But drawing into the Ronin as you last tile (or close to the end) is a disaster. I find it to be the best game piece there is. And there will be 2-3 moments in the game where you can use a Ronin to great effect. I like having it from the beginning so that I never miss the opportunity. I used it last night to score FOUR figures in one turn! WOW.<br />
<br />
So I think this is my new favourite opening hand. Very strong, extremely versatile. Note that you should be going for ties in the mid-late game since you run out of versatility later on and might need to finish the game quickly.  <br><BR><font size=1>09:49 11-02-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#CCCCCC>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#CCCCCC><font class="bfont"><B>The Bolshieviks</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#CCCCCC' ><font class="bfont"><img src=http://www.capitollegends.com/images/nikolaivolkoff150x150.jpg><br />
